## 1️⃣ **TypeScript: Proper Types/Interfaces, No `any`**

### 📚 **Fundamental Concepts**

#### **What is TypeScript?**
TypeScript is JavaScript with superpowers. It adds **static typing** to catch errors before your code runs.

```javascript
// JavaScript - Errors at runtime
function add(a, b) {
  return a + b; // What if a is "hello" and b is "world"?
}

add("hello", "world"); // "helloworld" - Might not be what you want!
```

```typescript
// TypeScript - Errors at compile time
function add(a: number, b: number): number {
  return a + b;
}

add("hello", "world"); // ❌ Error: Argument of type 'string' is not assignable to parameter of type 'number'
```

#### **Why "No `any`"?**
The `any` type tells TypeScript "I don't care about type checking here" - this defeats the purpose!

```typescript
// ❌ BAD - Using 'any'
function processUser(user: any) {
  return user.name.toUpperCase(); // What if user.name doesn't exist?
}

// ✅ GOOD - Proper typing
interface User {
  name: string;
  email: string;
  age: number;
}

function processUser(user: User): string {
  return user.name.toUpperCase(); // TypeScript knows name exists and is a string
}
```

### 🏗️ **Types vs Interfaces**

#### **Types**
- Can represent unions, primitives, complex types
- More flexible for creating unions and conditional types

```typescript
// Union types
type Status = 'pending' | 'completed' | 'failed';

// Complex types
type ApiResponse<T> = {
  success: boolean;
  data: T;
  message?: string;
};
```

#### **Interfaces**
- Best for object shapes and class implementations
- Support declaration merging
- More readable for object contracts

```typescript
interface Task {
  id: string;
  title: string;
  status: Status;
  completedAt?: Date; // Optional property
}

interface TaskManager {
  tasks: Task[];
  addTask(task: Omit<Task, 'id'>): Task;
  completeTask(id: string): void;
}
```

